domain_key|pattern_key|score_shape|closing_summary|core_gift|core_trap|development_edge|memorable_line|status|lookup_key
leadership-approach|process_results_vision_people|concentrated|With Process clearly strongest, start from the condition it gives you: the steps, standards, and handovers are clear enough to follow. Keep Results, Vision, and People available so the response can widen when the situation asks for more than the first move.|Process gives the work order, repeatability, and a dependable way for others to follow. Results, Vision, and People extend that value when the work needs decision, ownership, and follow-through, direction, meaning, and future consequence, or trust, communication, and shared commitment.|The pattern can tighten when method keeps absorbing attention after the work is clear enough to move. People may need to enter earlier when the first response has already created enough structure.|Bring in People when trust, communication, inclusion, or commitment needs more direct attention. Do this while Process is still working, so range arrives before the response becomes too narrow.|Process gives the start; People keeps the range in view.|active|leadership-approach::process_results_vision_people::concentrated
leadership-approach|process_results_vision_people|paired|Read Process and Results as a working pair. Let the steps, standards, and handovers are clear enough to follow sit alongside the outcome, owner, and next move are clear, then bring in Vision and People when the work needs more range.|Process and Results together connect sequence, standards, and dependable structure with decision, ownership, and follow-through. This can make the work easier to understand, carry, and sustain.|The pair can take too much space when Vision or People is needed to complete the picture. The risk is a context mismatch: the work may need trust, communication, and shared commitment sooner than the pair expects.|Bring in Vision when the work needs a stronger reason, future frame, or consequence to guide the next move. Bring in People when trust, communication, inclusion, or commitment needs more direct attention. The pair stays steadier when these checks arrive before the answer feels settled.|Process and Results carry the centre; People keeps the work rounded.|active|leadership-approach::process_results_vision_people::paired
leadership-approach|process_results_vision_people|graduated|Read the order as a stepped pattern of influence: Process, then Results, then Vision, with People added deliberately. The closing point is to follow that order while still making room for trust, communication, and shared commitment.|The rank order gives the work a clear movement from sequence, standards, and dependable structure through decision, ownership, and follow-through and direction, meaning, and future consequence. People adds the final range when the situation calls for trust, communication, and shared commitment.|The sequence can become too closed when later signals are left until the situation has already tightened. People matters when the work now needs trust, communication, and shared commitment.|Bring in People when trust, communication, inclusion, or commitment needs more direct attention. Treat it as part of the full order rather than an emergency move.|Follow the order, then make space for People before the work closes in.|active|leadership-approach::process_results_vision_people::graduated
leadership-approach|process_results_vision_people|balanced|Several leadership responses are available here. Use the rank order as a map: Process, Results, Vision, and People. Context decides which signal should be most visible, so name the need clearly before the work moves on.|The value is range across Process, Results, Vision, and People. The work can move through delivery, structure, direction, or trust while staying tied to the situation in front of you.|Balanced range can still become unclear if the current need is unnamed. Others need to know whether the moment calls for Process, Results, Vision, and People.|Name the current need before changing emphasis. Then bring in People when trust, communication, and shared commitment would make the response clearer.|Name the need, then use the signal that fits it.|active|leadership-approach::process_results_vision_people::balanced
